Salem, Massachusetts

By Timothy Lutts

==

A Lesson From The Earl Of Cardigan

What Next For Solar Stocks?

Google vs. Amazon

==

The first order of business today is apologizing to all veterans of the
Korean War for the omission of that event in my table listing the numbers
of Americans killed in wars.  To those of you who wrote, thank you.  Below
you'll find a corrected table, along with the numbers of casualties from a
few other wars as well.

Revolutionary War                  25,324
Indian Wars                                6,125
War of 1812                               2,260
Mexican War                           13,283
Civil War - North                  363,020
Civil War - South                 199,110
Spanish American War           2,893
Philippines War                        4,273
World War I                           116,708
World War II                          408,306
Korean War                             54,246
Vietnam War                           58,219
Iraq War                                      3,461 and counting

Those are the big ones.  Unlisted are dozens of smaller conflicts,
including the Barbary Wars of 1801-1815, the China Boxer Rebellion of
1900, Haiti in 1915-1920, Grenada in 1983 and Desert Shield/Storm in 1990
and 1991.

Many of these wars helped make the U.S. a better and safer place, and for
that I am grateful. Some campaigns are of questionable value in hindsight,
but that fact in no way demeans the contributions of those servicemen who
paid with their lives.

A little reflection on that subject, in fact, brings to mind Alfred, Lord
Tennyson's "Their's not to reason why, Their's but to do and die." The
quote is from "The Charge of the Light Brigade," by Tennyson, who wrote
the poem to honor the British who died or were wounded during the Battle
of Balaclava in 1854 in the Crimean War.

In the century and a half since then, the poem has come to symbolize both
the courage and tragedy of warfare, in part because the odds were so
heavily against the British.  Their 673 cavalrymen were grossly outmatched
by 20 battalions (5240 cavalry, thousands more infantry and 50 pieces of
artillery) of Russians.

But their "courage" was partly the result of poor communications!
The commanding officer, the Earl of Cardigan, had received written orders
to take the cavalry rapidly to the front and there prevent the enemy from
carrying away their guns.  But those orders were interpreted (by either
Cardigan, his subordinates or both) to mean the guns that could be seen a
mile down the valley, when in fact the orders referred to guns much closer
. . .that Cardigan couldn't see!

And so he charged, taking his troops all the way to the guns and back,
while taking fire from front, back and flank along the way.

And the tragedy?  Well, it wasn't the massacre that's popularly
remembered.  Of the 673 cavalrymen, 118 were killed and 127 were wounded.
Heavy casualties were inflicted on the Russian side, too, but exact
numbers are unknown.

So why does the incident remain in our consciousness in the 21st century? 
Because of Tennnyson.  Back then, poetry was a major media form, and the
dissemination of his poem, published less than seven weeks after the
battle, inflamed and legitimatized the sentiments about the incident that
persist to this day.

In the 21st century, of course, poetry has far less influence; in its
place we have television, radio and YouTube.  But the power of the media,
in the hands of both institutions and individuals, remains undiminished. 
And that, in general, is a good thing.  (Thoughts creep in here about the
restraints on freedom of speech in China, but I'll hold them for another
time.)

Interestingly, the official investigations that followed the battle at
Balaclava hastened the end of the British practice of buying commissions,
which until then had been the surest way for a wealthy man to become an
officer.  The Earl of Cardigan, for example, had paid 40,000 pounds for
his commission.  Rational minds concluded the military was better served
by men who had gained valuable experience by rising through the ranks.

Of such details is history made.

