==

Back in the present day, the bull market continues, with the Dow, the S&P
500 and the NYSE advance-decline line all hitting new highs yesterday.

Overall, most stocks on our radar screen are acting very well, and it's a
great time to be aggressively invested.  In fact some day, we will look
back on this time with longing.

But solar power stocks are at a Moment of Truth (MOT) here.  They've
corrected over the past few weeks so that most are sitting at support.  If
that support fails from here, the recovery is likely to be long.  But if
support holds here - and so far it's holding - this could prove to be a
great entry point.

My guess is that the stocks will hold, and the reason is simple.
It's that the global push to clean energy is so big, and so early in its
development, that's it's nearly impossible for this trend to be over yet.

Part of the story here is the change in consciousness among American
consumers, and that's big.

Consider bottled water, for instance.  In most cases, this water is no
safer or better tasting than tap water.  Yet today, everyone's got a
bottle, from the ministers around the table at the G8 conference to the
kids in Little League. It's a triumph of marketing; Americans spent $11
billion last year buying some 83 billion gallons of bottled water.  But
where do all those plastic bottles end up?  Recycled (which takes energy)
or in landfills (which pollutes).

So now fine dining establishments in New York City and elsewhere are
tuning in to the sensibilities of their customers and offering . . . tap
water.  And I'm betting that's just the beginning of a retreat from the
bottled water craze.

In a similar vein, the city of Las Vegas, trying hard to "do the right
thing," offered tax credits for businesses that built energy-efficient
buildings.  Trouble is, the administration woefully underestimated demand
and wound up retroactively modifying it to shrink those advantages.

Back on the consumer side, individuals continue to line up for
hybrid-powered cars, not necessarily because they will save any money
doing so but because it's good for the earth.  At the extreme, there's the
new Lexus LS 600h, a luxury sedan that will get about 18 miles per gallon
in real-life driving and cost over $100,000 when it goes on sale this
summer.

And then there's the price of oil, which remains high.  In fact, some
analysts claim the long-term uptrend is still intact and predict that oil
will hit $100 per barrel in the years ahead!

For all these fundamental reasons, I don't think the solar stocks are done
yet.

And there's one more reason.  Triple-digit revenue growth in a company
(100% or better) is one of the most reliable indicators that a stock will
become a winner for us.  When we see a company growing revenues at that
rate, we know something big is happening fast, and we know that the stock
often rewards early and patient investors.

 But what about the current situation, when almost every company in the
whole industry boasts that rapid growth?

Well, we've never been in that boat before.  The early days of the
Internet boom saw something similar, but many of those companies weren't
making money, and many of them never did!  Most solar power companies are
making great profits right here, and I believe their future is bright for
both them and their stocks.

I've mentioned individual names before, and no doubt I will again in the
future.  For details, you should be reading either Cabot Market Letter of
Cabot Top Ten Report.

