==

Finally, a little face-off between Google (GOOG) and Amazon (AMZN).
Which stock would you rather own?

Google is one of America's favorite companies today.  You can't help but
love the service, which is a dream come true to knowledge junkies like me,
and increasingly valuable to companies large and small all over the globe.
 Also, Google owns YouTube, which is a cultural home run with a bright
future.  And everyone knows that Google hires the brightest people in the
country.

In fact, today's Boston Globe had a puff piece on Google office in
Cambridge (right outside Boston), where employees play video games, have
lava lamps and maybe do some work.

And how are the numbers?  On the revenue side, Google shows decelerating
growth over the past two years, with the revenue growth rate decreasing
from 98% to 63%.  On the earnings side, the deceleration has not been as
linear, but there as well, the latest quarter shows the lowest growth rate
in the past two years.  Profit margins, however, have always been very
impressive, and they just hit an all-time high of 31.6%.  If these trends
continue, Google will continue to grow, at an ever-slower rate
(notwithstanding the occasional huge acquisition), and continue to make
ever more money, a fact that eventually should lead to higher stock
prices.

But what does the stock's chart say?

First, that GOOG has underperformed the broad market since the end of
2005, when it hit 475. Today it's up just 5% since then, while the S&P 500
is up 22% and the Nasdaq is up 18%.

Second, that the stock hit an all-time high of 513 in the third week of
January of this year, and now, at 500, is working to break out above that
level.  If it can, great; such a breakout might spark the stock's next
uptrend.  On the other hand, every day waiting for that breakout is a day
that you could be making money in a growth stock that's actually going
up.

Yet every month, more and more institutions own Google!  There are now
more than 800 mutual funds on board.  In our office we have an unofficial
red line at 1000, meaning that when the number of institutions that own a
stock tops 1000, it's so well-respected that its best days as an
investment are likely past.

Conclusion:  Google is one of the greatest companies on earth, but because
a majority of investors hold the same opinion, it's no longer a great
stock, and you should always be careful not to confuse the company with
the stock.

Which brings us to Amazon.

Amazon (AMZN) was one of our greatest investments.  The Cabot Market
Letter held it from January 1998 to January 2000, racking up a 1290%
profit in the process.  After that, it crashed, like all Internet stocks,
and we were very happy to be out of it.

In November 2002, when it was trading at 22, Amazon earned a spot in Cabot
Top Ten Report and it ran all the way to 61, eleven months later. That was
followed by three years of sub-par performance that only a mother could
love.

But just five weeks ago, on May 1, Amazon again earned a spot in Cabot Top
Ten Report.  It was trading at 61 at the time, having just vaulted 28% -
in one day, and on massive volume! - on the strength of its quarterly
earnings report.  But was that too late to buy?  No way!  Editor Mike
Cintolo told Cabot Top Ten Report readers to buy there and today, AMZN is
15% higher.

Now, when I first reported this on May 3, I told you I didn't like Amazon
as an investment.  My main reservation was that the company was too well
known and respected.  But I've considered some more facts since then,
including the stock's trading over the past month, and I've changed my
mind.

Looking at the fundamentals, I see something quite different at Amazon
than I do at Google.  I see accelerating growth of revenues over the past
five quarters, the result of investments that Amazon has made in recent
years.  I see earnings growth of 117% in the latest quarter, as those
investments pay off on the bottom line.  I see profit margins of 3.7%,
minuscule compared to Google's (and not comparable because the companies
are in different industries), but a real improvement from the margins of
the past year.  And I see only 268 mutual funds on board . . . and no puff
pieces in newspapers.

And what of the chart?  Well, it's strong, which is how it earned a spot
in Cabot Top Ten Report. In breaking out above 61, it exceeded its old
2003 high, which left it free to head for the old high of 2000 at 113. 
And in the month since then it's climbed to 70, and held there very
tightly, drawing no pressure from sellers.

Conclusion: Amazon, out of the spotlight for so long, is now under
accumulation by institutions who recognize the new trend of accelerating
growth, and buying on normal corrections is recommended.

